1
00:00:01,668 --> 00:00:03,712
Pay attention this time.
I hate repeating myself.

2
00:00:04,505 --> 00:00:06,673
Tommy Donnelly always wanted
to be an artist, right?

3
00:00:06,924 --> 00:00:08,133
Kate Farrell knew that.

4
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:10,177
And she had
a famous artist friend.

5
00:00:10,260 --> 00:00:11,887
I think it might be good
for you to meet him.

6
00:00:12,137 --> 00:00:15,224
Dokey had a friend, too.
Councilman Jack Trevor.

7
00:00:15,599 --> 00:00:17,559
Jack told Dokey
he better start playin' nice

8
00:00:17,643 --> 00:00:18,644
with the Italians.

9
00:00:18,852 --> 00:00:21,230
Jimmy was all about
playin' nice with others.

10
00:00:21,480 --> 00:00:23,357
Like Whitey's uncle,
Bob the Mouth.

11
00:00:23,565 --> 00:00:25,192
But Bob wanted the money
Jimmy owed him,

12
00:00:25,317 --> 00:00:26,485
and he wanted Jimmy dead.

13
00:00:26,693 --> 00:00:28,487
We both know your uncle's
gonna wanna kill me.

14
00:00:28,529 --> 00:00:29,530
Bye-bye, Bob.

15
00:00:30,822 --> 00:00:33,367
So the bookmaking business
was back to usual.

16
00:00:33,534 --> 00:00:35,327
(GRUNTING)

17
00:00:35,577 --> 00:00:37,371
Except for one tiny detail.

18
00:00:37,454 --> 00:00:39,206
Nicky found out they stole
the book from him

19
00:00:39,289 --> 00:00:41,124
and he wanted
the business back.

20
00:00:41,375 --> 00:00:43,377
Jenny wanted her dad back,
the way he was

21
00:00:43,460 --> 00:00:45,170
before he started
losin' his marbles.

22
00:00:45,212 --> 00:00:47,005
I lost a little memory,
that's all.

23
00:00:47,089 --> 00:00:49,424
Yeah. And I'm on vacation
in the Bahamas.

24
00:00:51,718 --> 00:00:54,471
Joey, the warden says
you haven't been eating.

25
00:00:54,721 --> 00:00:57,432
Look around.
I mean, this is it, forever.

26
00:00:59,226 --> 00:01:00,352
There's nothin' left
to look forward to,

27
00:01:00,435 --> 00:01:01,854
no hopes, no dreams.

28
00:01:03,772 --> 00:01:06,108
It's a terrible thing
to take away a man's dream.

29
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:08,068
Try to sit up.
Eat something.

30
00:01:08,735 --> 00:01:10,320
And we can discuss
these feelings.

31
00:01:10,404 --> 00:01:12,447
That's the thing
about most of us
from the neighborhood,

32
00:01:12,531 --> 00:01:13,699
you know that?

33
00:01:14,908 --> 00:01:16,076
We all reach this point

34
00:01:16,159 --> 00:01:17,494
where there's nothin' left
to aim for.

35
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:20,330
But I'm gettin' ahead
of myself.

36
00:01:24,084 --> 00:01:27,504
You know, maybe I will just
have one of those carrots.

37
00:01:28,839 --> 00:01:31,466
See, Tommy Donnelly's dream

38
00:01:31,592 --> 00:01:33,468
was to pursue
all that art crap.

39
00:01:34,344 --> 00:01:37,222
Now, it's a little gay for me,
but for Tommy,

40
00:01:37,306 --> 00:01:39,266
it was the only thing
other than Jenny Reilly

41
00:01:39,349 --> 00:01:40,893
that he ever really wanted.

42
00:01:41,602 --> 00:01:44,396
And he decided to go for it,
once and for all.

43
00:01:45,647 --> 00:01:46,982
Hello?

44
00:01:47,065 --> 00:01:48,400
MUNST: In the back.

45
00:02:03,457 --> 00:02:05,209
You're Kate's friend.

46
00:02:05,959 --> 00:02:07,377
Tommy Donnelly.

47
00:02:08,462 --> 00:02:10,756
It's an honor to meet you,
Mr. Munst.

48
00:02:10,797 --> 00:02:12,090
Mmm-hmm.

49
00:02:14,301 --> 00:02:15,469
(GROANS)

50
00:02:23,602 --> 00:02:25,312
What are you doing?

51
00:02:26,813 --> 00:02:28,106
I thought
I would show you
some of my...

52
00:02:28,190 --> 00:02:29,566
No, no. Hey! Seriously,

53
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:31,443
seriously,
put that away.

54
00:02:32,152 --> 00:02:33,529
Kate said you wanted
to see some of my work.

55
00:02:33,654 --> 00:02:35,948
Please! I can't handle
amateur crap

56
00:02:36,073 --> 00:02:37,282
this early
in the morning.

57
00:02:43,247 --> 00:02:45,541
Maybe there's been
some mistake.

58
00:02:48,669 --> 00:02:50,671
Kate said you
wanted this job.

59
00:02:51,213 --> 00:02:52,214
Job?

60
00:02:52,631 --> 00:02:54,716
Are we having
language issues here?

61
00:02:55,384 --> 00:02:57,427
The intern job.
You want it?

62
00:02:59,012 --> 00:03:01,098
Depends. What do I have to do?

63
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:03,350
Oh, now we got
contingencies, right?

64
00:03:05,185 --> 00:03:06,812
No. I'll take it.

65
00:03:07,855 --> 00:03:09,022
All right.

66
00:03:09,147 --> 00:03:12,860
Get me some coffee,
and here,

67
00:03:12,860 --> 00:03:14,319
some stuff I need done.

68
00:03:17,531 --> 00:03:18,824
There a problem?

69
00:03:18,866 --> 00:03:19,992
No.

70
00:03:20,868 --> 00:03:22,995
I'm on it.
Well, not yet, you're not.

71
00:03:23,245 --> 00:03:25,914
If you was on it,
I would see your
tootsies movin'.

72
00:03:31,753 --> 00:03:33,130
Now, Jimmy
had dreams too.

73
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:35,090
But he didn't just want
his name in lights,

74
00:03:35,174 --> 00:03:37,217
he wanted
his whole life in lights.

75
00:03:37,467 --> 00:03:40,220
So he started with a new sign
for the Firecracker.

76
00:03:51,148 --> 00:03:52,649
I don't get it.

77
00:03:52,900 --> 00:03:54,776
What's not to get?
There's a flame
and a cracker.

78
00:03:54,860 --> 00:03:56,195
Put it together.

79
00:03:56,320 --> 00:03:57,821
Flame cracker?

80
00:03:57,905 --> 00:03:59,531
Oh, I get it.
Firecracker.

81
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,158
It's a little
confusing.

82
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:02,784
Don't you guys
watch commercials?

83
00:04:03,076 --> 00:04:05,746
The ones you don't understand,
but they make you think?

84
00:04:05,829 --> 00:04:06,830
That's this!

85
00:04:06,914 --> 00:04:09,708
Abstract.
I don't get abstract.

86
00:04:10,459 --> 00:04:13,128
Why didn't you just
print the words,
"The Firecracker"?

87
00:04:13,337 --> 00:04:14,379
'Cause that's what
the old sign said.

88
00:04:14,505 --> 00:04:16,006
We're startin' new here.

89
00:04:17,424 --> 00:04:18,759
Okay, we got a problem.

90
00:04:18,842 --> 00:04:19,885
What's this?

91
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:21,386
Louie Downtown's
cell phone.

92
00:04:21,428 --> 00:04:22,930
The one you were
supposed to throw away?

93
00:04:23,055 --> 00:04:25,015
Yeah, but that's
not the problem.

94
00:04:29,478 --> 00:04:31,522
That's how you get rid
of a cell phone, Kevin!

95
00:04:31,605 --> 00:04:32,689
Guess I should
have done that.

96
00:04:32,773 --> 00:04:34,066
You guess?

97
00:04:35,901 --> 00:04:38,445
Okay, Nicky Cottero
made a bet with you

98
00:04:38,529 --> 00:04:39,613
on Louie's cell phone?

99
00:04:39,696 --> 00:04:41,114
Yeah, on that cell phone
right there.

100
00:04:41,198 --> 00:04:42,241
That's what I'm tellin' you.

101
00:04:42,449 --> 00:04:43,617
And he lost?

102
00:04:43,700 --> 00:04:45,327
A thousand bucks.

103
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:48,580
And he came to meet you last
night to pay off the bet.

104
00:04:48,664 --> 00:04:49,706
Yeah.

105
00:04:49,790 --> 00:04:50,874
But he didn't pay you?

106
00:04:50,958 --> 00:04:52,918
No, he said
he needed another day.

107
00:04:53,460 --> 00:04:55,587
That doesn't make any sense.
He should have killed you.

108
00:04:55,712 --> 00:04:56,797
Yeah, I know.

109
00:04:56,880 --> 00:04:58,048
But I didn't think
it'd be a good idea

110
00:04:58,131 --> 00:04:59,174
to press the issue.

111
00:04:59,758 --> 00:05:01,301
He's playin'
games with us.

112
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:03,637
Or he wants to make
a deal with us.

113
00:05:03,720 --> 00:05:04,721
What kind of deal?

114
00:05:04,805 --> 00:05:06,515
I don't know,
but if someone
stole my business,

115
00:05:06,598 --> 00:05:07,558
I'd want to kill them.

116
00:05:08,267 --> 00:05:10,310
Unless I thought that
they could make me money.

117
00:05:11,687 --> 00:05:12,896
Sean, get your car.

118
00:05:13,272 --> 00:05:14,439
Where we goin', Jimmy?

119
00:05:14,523 --> 00:05:17,484
You're not goin' anywhere.
You screwed up enough.

120
00:05:19,111 --> 00:05:20,529
Where are you goin'?

121
00:05:20,821 --> 00:05:23,407
Nicky asked for another day,
right? That's today.

122
00:05:23,866 --> 00:05:25,826
We're gonna go collect
what's owed us.

123
00:05:32,166 --> 00:05:33,834
(SMOKE DETECTOR BEEPING)

124
00:05:33,917 --> 00:05:34,960
Dad?

125
00:05:39,506 --> 00:05:40,841
(COUGHING)

126
00:05:42,342 --> 00:05:43,385
Dad?

127
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:48,348
(BEEPING STOPS)

128
00:05:49,808 --> 00:05:51,435
Dad!

129
00:05:59,026 --> 00:06:00,068
Hello?

130
00:06:01,028 --> 00:06:02,529
You open?
No.

131
00:06:03,864 --> 00:06:06,241
Sorry, just lookin'
for some breakfast.

132
00:06:06,825 --> 00:06:07,993
I smell bacon.

133
00:06:08,035 --> 00:06:09,161
How did you get in here?

134
00:06:09,203 --> 00:06:10,537
Door was open.

135
00:06:28,263 --> 00:06:33,602
(GUNSHO TS)

136
00:06:41,401 --> 00:06:43,403
(GRUNTING)

137
00:06:47,950 --> 00:06:49,952
JOEY. Now, Dokey
had a dream, too.

138
00:06:50,244 --> 00:06:52,037
He wanted to be
his brother Huey.

139
00:06:52,287 --> 00:06:54,623
Councilman Jack Trevor
recently told Dokey

140
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:56,041
how to achieve that dream.

141
00:06:56,750 --> 00:06:59,336
Unfortunately, things kept
getting in the way.

142
00:06:59,419 --> 00:07:00,379
Councilman?

143
00:07:00,546 --> 00:07:02,965
I'm the chair of the buildings
committee. I'm busy.

144
00:07:03,215 --> 00:07:06,009
Today, I get a call from
this contractor down here.

145
00:07:06,093 --> 00:07:08,971
He's been getting grief from
this overzealous inspector.

146
00:07:09,179 --> 00:07:12,599
So here I am, in the flesh,
taking care of his problem.

147
00:07:13,267 --> 00:07:15,519
This inspector, next week,

148
00:07:15,644 --> 00:07:18,021
will be overzealous
in Staten Island.

149
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:19,940
Is there a problem, Jack?

150
00:07:20,315 --> 00:07:22,234
Bob Kelly, you know him?

151
00:07:22,276 --> 00:07:24,027
Yeah, I know him.
Bob the Mouth.

152
00:07:24,111 --> 00:07:26,071
Bookie.
He's a slob. Why?

153
00:07:29,867 --> 00:07:31,994
When I asked you
to have no more bodies

154
00:07:32,077 --> 00:07:34,538
showin' up on the front pages
of the city's newspapers,

155
00:07:34,663 --> 00:07:36,999
you misunderstood
and thought it would
be a good idea

156
00:07:37,124 --> 00:07:40,252
to have fat bookies flyin' out
of 17-story windows.

157
00:07:40,377 --> 00:07:41,879
It can't happen.

158
00:07:43,088 --> 00:07:45,215
Jack, you talk to me like
I'm some street punk again,

159
00:07:45,299 --> 00:07:47,259
and I'm gonna
cut your tongue out.

160
00:07:47,301 --> 00:07:48,802
We had a deal.

161
00:07:49,219 --> 00:07:52,931
If I can't shake your hand and
expect you to live up to it,

162
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:55,726
then you gotta tell me now.

163
00:07:56,643 --> 00:07:59,021
I'll see what happened,
and I'll look into it, okay?

164
00:07:59,396 --> 00:08:01,523
And you'll do it without
anyone else getting killed,

165
00:08:01,607 --> 00:08:02,608
I hope.

166
00:08:02,941 --> 00:08:04,693
That's what we need.

167
00:08:04,943 --> 00:08:08,447
Derek Farrell, you know my
chief of staff, Trish Hughes?

168
00:08:08,572 --> 00:08:10,574
Yes. Nice to see you again.

169
00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:11,909
I'll wait in the car.

170
00:08:11,992 --> 00:08:14,077
No, no, no.
We're done here.

171
00:08:23,879 --> 00:08:25,255
Let's get out of here.

172
00:08:36,183 --> 00:08:38,519
Hey, we're closed.
I'm just settin' up
for the night.

173
00:08:38,602 --> 00:08:39,853
I'm lookin'
for Nicky Cottero.

174
00:08:39,937 --> 00:08:43,607
He usually comes in later.
Much later.

175
00:08:46,860 --> 00:08:49,154
What about that stooge
he's always hanging out with?

176
00:08:49,238 --> 00:08:50,489
What's his name, Vinnie?

177
00:08:50,531 --> 00:08:52,157
Hey, listen,
I don't know exactly
what you're looking for,

178
00:08:52,241 --> 00:08:53,283
but whatever it is,

179
00:08:53,367 --> 00:08:55,744
do me a favor
and look for it
somewhere else.

180
00:08:55,911 --> 00:08:58,121
Hey, I told you
not to come back here.
Nicky is not here.

181
00:08:58,163 --> 00:09:00,207
Take another step,
I'll chop your thumbs off!

182
00:09:03,085 --> 00:09:05,587
You do know that Nicky Cottero
owns this bar, right?

183
00:09:05,671 --> 00:09:07,798
The last guy
who didn't pay
his bar tab

184
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:09,508
got a meat hook
up his ass.

185
00:09:09,883 --> 00:09:11,009
What do you think's
gonna happen to you

186
00:09:11,093 --> 00:09:12,135
if you rob the place?

187
00:09:13,053 --> 00:09:14,137
What's the matter
with this guy?

188
00:09:14,221 --> 00:09:15,305
I can't talk
to him either.

189
00:09:15,430 --> 00:09:17,057
Tell Nicky that
Jimmy Donnelly
stopped by

190
00:09:17,182 --> 00:09:18,767
to pick up
the thousand he owed.

191
00:09:19,476 --> 00:09:21,937
He wants to talk to me,
he can call me
at the Firecracker.

192
00:09:25,732 --> 00:09:27,025
Hit it!

193
00:09:28,193 --> 00:09:30,654
COP: I'll put the word out,
but not much I can
do officially.

194
00:09:30,737 --> 00:09:32,614
He's only missin' for what,
two hours?

195
00:09:33,073 --> 00:09:34,533
I know something's wrong.

196
00:09:34,575 --> 00:09:35,909
Has he gone missing before?

197
00:09:36,618 --> 00:09:39,496
No, but he's been having
some memory problems,

198
00:09:40,372 --> 00:09:41,707
and, I mean,
just once in a while...

199
00:09:41,790 --> 00:09:44,042
So then he has
done this before?

200
00:09:44,793 --> 00:09:46,420
He's never been
missing before.

201
00:09:46,587 --> 00:09:49,756
Did he have any ID on him?
Driver's license, ID bracelet?

202
00:09:49,756 --> 00:09:50,799
No, he left his wallet.

203
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:53,010
I assume he's not registered?

204
00:09:53,093 --> 00:09:54,052
Registered?

205
00:09:54,178 --> 00:09:55,262
As an Alzheimer's patient?

206
00:09:55,387 --> 00:09:57,556
The Safe Return program,
you know about it?

207
00:09:57,723 --> 00:09:59,057
He doesn't have Alzheimer's.

208
00:09:59,141 --> 00:10:00,434
How do you know that?

209
00:10:00,517 --> 00:10:02,311
You took him to a doctor?

210
00:10:02,394 --> 00:10:04,146
No, he wouldn't go.

211
00:10:04,521 --> 00:10:05,814
So you thought
it'd be better to wait

212
00:10:05,898 --> 00:10:08,025
until he walked out
the front door and got lost.

213
00:10:10,694 --> 00:10:12,404
Can I use your pen?

214
00:10:17,451 --> 00:10:18,493
I'm gonna give you my cell

215
00:10:18,577 --> 00:10:20,412
so if you hear anything
you could call me.

216
00:10:31,048 --> 00:10:32,841
Hi, Vincent.

217
00:10:32,966 --> 00:10:35,219
Why don't you call me Vinnie
like everybody else?

218
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:36,929
I mean, why does it
have to be Vincent?

219
00:10:37,012 --> 00:10:38,764
I like Vincent.

220
00:10:38,805 --> 00:10:40,641
Anybody can be a Vinnie.

221
00:10:40,974 --> 00:10:42,768
Yeah, well,
I like being Vinnie.

222
00:10:44,311 --> 00:10:45,687
What's up?

223
00:10:47,814 --> 00:10:49,274
Guess I should let
you boys talk.

224
00:10:49,358 --> 00:10:51,193
Oh, no, no, no.
Stay here.

225
00:10:52,778 --> 00:10:53,820
Okay.

226
00:10:53,904 --> 00:10:55,781
Well, we got a response.

227
00:10:55,948 --> 00:10:57,616
From the Donnellys, right?
Yeah.

228
00:10:57,741 --> 00:10:59,535
But it might not be
the one you wanted.

229
00:10:59,618 --> 00:11:02,246
He robbed us for the $1,000
we owe him.

230
00:11:05,290 --> 00:11:07,251
Somebody robbed this bar
and you're laughing?

231
00:11:07,334 --> 00:11:09,336
No, it's all right, baby.

232
00:11:09,878 --> 00:11:11,880
Nothin' I didn't expect.

233
00:11:14,341 --> 00:11:15,509
MUNST: Tommy!

234
00:11:18,303 --> 00:11:19,513
Coming!

235
00:11:26,353 --> 00:11:28,772
JOEY. Sometimes it's a little
late to go for our dreams.

236
00:11:28,981 --> 00:11:31,942
It's then that you realize
it's either give up the dream

237
00:11:32,025 --> 00:11:33,485
or come up with another.

238
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:36,572
Kate came up with Tommy.

239
00:11:36,697 --> 00:11:39,491
Thought I'd see how
your first day was going.

240
00:11:39,575 --> 00:11:41,910
Thank you for the job.

241
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:43,745
Don't thank me yet.

242
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:45,747
Munst is a slave driver.

243
00:11:46,957 --> 00:11:49,209
I see he's got you
doing the easy work.

244
00:11:49,543 --> 00:11:52,337
I'm a mess.
And that wonderful smell?

245
00:11:52,588 --> 00:11:54,006
That's me, too.

246
00:11:54,047 --> 00:11:56,258
No, you look good.

247
00:11:57,301 --> 00:11:59,011
I should let you
get back to work.

248
00:12:00,888 --> 00:12:03,515
We have to set up a time
for Matthew's next
art lesson.

249
00:12:03,724 --> 00:12:04,808
Sure.

250
00:12:06,435 --> 00:12:07,895
Don't be too hard on him.

251
00:12:07,978 --> 00:12:09,188
Mmm.

252
00:12:15,402 --> 00:12:17,154
Good-lookin' widow.

253
00:12:19,031 --> 00:12:22,492
It's okay.
Everybody needs
a benefactor.

254
00:12:23,202 --> 00:12:25,287
In my day,
I had more than one.

255
